25|$|Wright invited {{national}} and local leaders to meet in Philadelphia to formulate plans to set aside February 1 each year to memorialize {{the signing of the}} 13th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution by President Abraham Lincoln on February 1, 1865, which freed all U.S. slaves. One year after Wright's death in 1947, both houses of the U.S. Congress passed a bill to make February 1 National Freedom Day. The holiday proclamation was signed into law on June 30, 1948, by President Harry Truman. It was the forerunner to <b>Black</b> <b>History</b> Day and later <b>Black</b> <b>History</b> Month, officially recognized in 1976, though began by Carter G. Woodson in 1926.|$|E
